LEFT JOIN in SQL

LEFT JOIN (or LEFT OUTER JOIN) is used to retrieve all records from the left table and the matching records from the right table based on a common column.

If there is no matching record in the right table, the result still includes the left table's row with NULL values for the right table's columns.

Syntax

SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table1
LEFT JOIN table2
ON table1.common_column = table2.common_column;

Example

Employee Table

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_id |
| ------ | -------- | ------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | 101     |
| 2      | Rahul    | 102     |
| 3      | Amit     | 103     |
| 4      | Neha     | 105     |

Department Table

| dept_id | dept_name |
| ------- | --------- |
| 101     | IT        |
| 102     | HR        |
| 103     | Finance   |
| 104     | Sales     |

Query

SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
LEFT JOIN Department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

Output

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_name |
| ------ | -------- | --------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | IT        |
| 2      | Rahul    | HR        |
| 3      | Amit     | Finance   |
| 4      | Neha     | NULL      |

Explanation:
  All records from the Employee table (left table) are returned.
  Matching records from the Department table (right table) are included.
  Since Neha (dept_id = 105) does not have a matching department, the dept_name is displayed as NULL.
  Sales (dept_id = 104) is not returned because there is no matching employee in the left table.
